    <etym xml:lang="ru">Очевидна связь с <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                    ><lang/><w>cʼqali</w><gloss><q>вода</q></gloss></mentioned>. Возможно, мы имеем
        дело не с заимствованием, а со старым субстратным отложением. Для полногласия в %icæqal%i
        ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cæxær"/> ‘огонь’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                ><lang/><w>cxeli</w></mentioned>), д. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_gælex"/> ‘раб’
            (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>glexi</w></mentioned>), <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_gærtam"/> ‘взятка’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>krtami</w></mentioned>), <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæbæda"/> ‘болтун’
            (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>qbedi</w></mentioned>) и др.; <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cællaq"/> ‘плеск’ представляет вариацию этого же слова, воспринимаемую
        ныне как звукоподражание.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>120, 325,
                526</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">There is an obvious connection with <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                ><lang/><w>cʼqali</w><gloss><q>water</q></gloss></mentioned>. Probably, we deal not
        with a borrowing but with an old substrate word. For the full vocalism in %icæqal%i cf. <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_cæxær"/> ‘fire’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>cxeli</w></mentioned>), Digor <ref type="xr" target="#entry_gælex"/> ‘slave’
            (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>glexi</w></mentioned>), <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_gærtam"/> ‘bribe’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>krtami</w></mentioned>), <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæbæda"/>
        ‘chatterbox’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>qbedi</w></mentioned>) etc.; <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cællaq"/> ‘splash’ represents the variantion of the same word which is
        percieved now as a sound symbolism.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>120, 325,
                526</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
